<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
This to Xyrloc post (even though it wasn't entirely directed at me):<P>Why should I be "sensitive"?<P>I'm not looking at the middle-east as an "axis of evil" but as a place that is "fubar" and a place where something must be done.<P>Why do I stereo-type the people of the middle-east into one large group? <P>Well for the most part I base most of what I say on history going back thousands of years i.e. the crusades all the way up to present day. A recent poll (wish I had a link) was done by Time/CNN from nearly all the Middle-Eastern countries and compiled. The results (again I could be off a touch) were something along the lines of 71% agree with Bin Laden's message, 90% feel strong anti-american sentiments, and 60% support groups such as Hamas, Islamic Jihad, Hezbollah, Al Qaida, et al. Basically 9 out of 10 people hate the US, 7 out of 10 support Osama bin Laden's message, and over half the people support or would support terrorist actions.<P>I would love to see your thesis when you are done. However, I don't understand why you come on here and blast everyone else and then don't offer a varying solution blaming it on the fact that your thesis isn't yet complete. You must have some idea or some stance you are taking. Even if this stance is not complete, please state it. I think the idea behind this topic was for addressing the Middle-East using constructive criticism.<P>I agree with you on one thing. The world is complex with many different people but it seems the unifying and dividing characteristic that all people share is religion. I realize there are hundreds of world-wide religions. The main ones that come to mine are Hindiusm, Buddhism, Christianity, Islam, and Judism (sorry for the spelling). <P>One thing is sad however...Religion is supposed to help people, bring inner-peace, develop people, and give them an understanding of the spiritual aspects of the world. Unfortunately, everyone thinks they are the right religion, have the right God, and as a result feud with other religions. In Islam, radical fundamentalist groups interpret the Qaran way wrong.  In particular the part that they interpret the most wrongly is the hidden 6th pillar of Islam (it's addressed as the 5 pillars of Islam). That pillar is Islamic "Jihad" which can be interpreted in several ways but the one it is most readily interpreted as is "holy war" or converting non-believers through conquest and domination.  <P>There needs to ultimately come a time when people love each other and try to work together.  I don't ever think a singular person will accomplish this but rather a higher spiritual being. But in the mean time, we can not allow ourselves to grow weak. The only way to stay safe is to be strong.  A strong offense is the best defense. During the Clinton administration, 40% of the U.S. military bases/installations were closed since there was supposedly "no inherent need" for them. We can not make this same mistake again. We must stay strong. We must be ready for the worse.<P>--------------------<P>Always Faithful<BR>LEEZARDZ 4 ever!<BR>Team  DAoC<BR>"That which does not kill us, makes us stronger." Nietzche
</FONT>
