<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
In terms of history post 1948...<P>-On the day Israel declared themselves a state in 1948, the Arab League (Saudi Arabia, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, Egypt) declared war on Israel.  Almost 500,000 Arabs, who lived amongst the Jews, left the new conrty to avoid the fighting.  These refugees are the beginning of the Palastinian movement despite the fact that they were fleeing from invading Arab armies.<P>-After the failed Arab Invasions, Transjordan (Jordan) annexed the "West Bank" and Egypt annexed the "Gaza Strip" in 1950. Despite this fact, no Arab contry welcomed the Palastinian refugees or allowed them to become citizens.<P>-Over the next 20 years Israel built the only industrialized economy and the only libral democracy that included a significant Arab minority that to this day enjoys more rights and privileges than any other Arab population in the region.  The only Arabs in the entire Middle East that can vote are Israely citizens.<P>-In 1964 the PLO was created and Yasser Arafat was deemed leader.  Most of the PLO's leadership was not even Palestinian.  Arafat was born in Egypt.  The original charter of the PLO called for "pushing the Jews into the sea.<P>-In 1967, Egypt, Syria and Jordan massed hundreds of thousands of troops on Israel borders including the "West Bank"  and "Gaza Strip" to finally finish the war they started back in 1948.  Isreal defeated them in what became known as the "6 Days War" and decided they needed to extend thier borders.  The reason for this decision was that the population centers of Israel where, in the case of Jerusalem, bordering and, in the case of Tel Aviv, only 11 miles away from Arabs whom they were at war with.  Isreal is in some places only 9 miles wide.  At this point, the Arab world had been at war with Israel for almost 20 years before the "occupied territories" were even an issue.<P>-In 1970 Jordan's King Hussein killed more Palestinians in one years than Israel has to date.<P>-In 1973, Arab nations again attacked Israel and were defeated.  After this conflict, Egyption president Anwar Sadat made formal peace with Israel in exchange for the concured (oil rich) Sinai and was subsequently assassinated by Islamic radicals.<P>-Arafat was offered 95% of the territory his negotiators demended, a self-governing authority in the "West Bank" and the "Gaza Strip," a 40,000 man armed police force, control of parts of Jerulalem, and leadway to create a Palestinian nation through the Olso Accords.  Arafat walked out on the peace process without even presenting a counter-offer and began the new terrorist wave known as "The Al-Aksa Intifada."  The Olso peace process was little more than a "Trojan Horse" luring Israel to allow Palestine to arm themselves over this 6 year period.<P>Simple facts... but what does it all mean?  It simply means that to the Arab powers that be value the destruction of Israel far more than they do the well-being of it's own people.  Individually, I'm sure many Palestinians have valid grievences with Israel (any war lasting 50 years will have plenty of these), but as a collective thier grievences should be directed at their leadership's exploitation of them to further thier platform of unaccecptence and hate.  This outcome in the Middle East is of course impossible with the repressive dictatorial governments, the state-run media propoganda, and the religious extreamism that is taught in their schools.  I don't say any of this as pro-Israely, I say this as purely pro-American.  <P>And as a pro-American I think we should swallow our pride with this situation and tip-toe along doing whatever needs to be done concerning Palestian/Israel to allow us to invade Iraq.  Overthrowing Saddam will do MUCH more to normalize this region than anything that can directly be done between Isreal and Palestain.
