s Iranian provocation and Syrian <BR>> > cooption. It is important that both countries understand -- Syria in <BR>> > the first instance -- that there will be a price to pay for this. And <BR>> > I think President Bush made that clear, and I think Israel is making - <BR>> > - or will make that clear. <BR>> > <BR>> > Q Sir, the current Israeli government has made explicit <BR>> > representations to the Bush administration that it is not trying to <BR>> > kill Arafat. You have made a connection between the war on terrorism <BR>> > being waged by Washington and your struggle in Israel. The Bush <BR>> > administration has made no bones about the idea that certain leaders <BR>> > on the adversary side in the global war on terrorism could be killed, <BR>> > and it would be acceptable. Do you rule that out as an option? And if <BR>> > Israel were to kill Arafat in waging this campaign, would there be a <BR>> > dire consequence for Israel? <BR>> > <BR>> > MR. NETANYAHU: Well, I have not suggested that Arafat be <BR>> > killed. I think a better idea would be to expel him. I was asked how <BR>> > would one do that, and I said, Well, put him on the Karine A, the <BR>> > terror ship that he received from Iran -- put that on the high seas <BR>> > and point it right outside the Banda Manday (ph) in the direction of <BR>> > Tehran, and let's see who takes him up. <BR>> > <BR>> > Q Is there any chance that you are wrong, that current Israeli <BR>> > actions will actually create more terrorists? <BR>> > <BR>> > MR. NETANYAHU: I don't think they create more terrorists. I <BR>> > think they might be -- they might be not sufficient to finish off <BR>> > this malignancy as I called it. It is possible to do a partial move <BR>> > that doesn't -- that actually backfires at the end of the day, <BR>> > because it is not complete, it is counterproductive. If you root out <BR>> > this terrorist infrastructure, and if you bring down Arafat's regime <BR>> > and expel Arafat from the region, and if you add the physical divide <BR>> > that I suggested between the main population centers of the <BR>> > Palestinians and Israel's population centers, I think you will have <BR>> > what is required. <BR>> > <BR>> > In any case, if you ask me based on my own record, we had -- <BR>> > we brought terrorism to a screeching halt -- a screeching halt. I <BR>> > mean, the number of suicide bombers that we had in the three years <BR>> > that I was in government was -- could be fit into one morning of what <BR>> > has been going on here -- and indeed before I took office. And the <BR>> > reason that is so is because my approach to terrorism is based on a <BR>> > doctrine that I helped shape. The former secretary of State actually <BR>> > affixed my name to it -- George Shultz called it the Netanyahu <BR>> > doctrine. And it simply says that the way you fight terrorists is not <BR>> > by fighting the terrorists in the first instance. You don't go <BR>> > looking for the needle in the haystack -- you go after the haystack. <BR>> > Or, if you will, you don't go after the suicide bomber or the suicide <BR>> > pilot, the kamikaze pilot who is coming at you. You can shoot him <BR>> > down, but then another guy will come. The way you get at the kamikaze <BR>> > pilots at the end of the day is you go after the carrier. And going <BR>> > after the carrier, you can do one of two things. You either strike at <BR>> > the carrier and force it to take another -- go elsewhere, change its <BR>> > direction. That's called deterrence. Or, you sink the carrier. <BR>> > <BR>> > Effectively, that's what the United States is doing right now. <BR>> > It is deterring some carriers -- deterring some terrorist regimes <BR>> > like Syria and Somalia and so on, and it's sinking others. It's <BR>> > already sunk the Taliban regime. It's about to sink Saddam's regime, <BR>> > and maybe there are others in the offing. These are the two options <BR>> > that you have. <BR>> > <BR>> > I have said for a long time, when I was prime minister, I <BR>> > deterred Arafat. It's fairly easy to do. I said to him, "Nothing will <BR>> > save your regime if you continue the kind of terrorism that you did <BR>> > under Rabin and Peres, I will bring you down." I had this message <BR>> > brought to him by an intermediary, a very soft-spoken Jerusalem <BR>> > lawyer, by the way, very soft-spoken. It was very clear: I will bring <BR>> > you down, you know. I don't care about American pressure. I don't <BR>> > care about the U.S. administration. I will bring you down. That got <BR>> > his attention. He stopped. He stopped. For two years after this <BR>> > message was delivered with some force, there was practically no <BR>> > terrorism, none at all. We had a record number of tourists visiting <BR>> > Israel and the Palestinian areas. Record investments in high-tech. As <BR>> > I told you, Israelis went to -- not only to Ramallah, they went to <BR>> > Jericho to a casino that I -- I said why not have a casino -- Las <BR>> > Vegas on Jericho. Why not? That's fine. <BR>> > <BR>> > But I'm telling you today that the principle of deterrence <BR>> > will not work vis-a-vis Arafat. He's beyond deterrence. He's got to <BR>> > go. You have only two options. Whatever else you do with al Qaeda, <BR>> > whatever else you do with Hamas, whatever else you do with Islamic <BR>> > Jihad, that doesn't count unless you get at the regime. And having <BR>> > deterred Arafat in the past and not being able to deter him now, you <BR>> > have to get rid of him just as surely as you have to get rid of the <BR>> > Taliban, and you did. <BR>> > <BR>> > SEN. KYL: Thank you very much. <BR>> > MR. NETANYAHU: Thank you. Good-bye.
